Inflammation is an adaptive mechanism used by the human immune system in response to microbial invasion or harmful stimulus (

). In general, inflammation is a complex process in human body involving a number of inflammatory mediators such as reactive oxygen species (ROS), interleukin (IL)-1β, tumor necrosis factor-α (TNF-α), IL-6, nitric oxide (NO), and NF-kB, etc. (

). In addition, some signaling proteins such as extracellular signal-related kinase (ERK)-1/2, p38 mitogen-activated protein kinase (MAPK), c-Jun NH 
2
-terminal kinase (JNK), and phosphoinositide 3-kinase (PI3K)/Akt and NF-κB also control the inflammation response (

). Up to now, in spite of many marketed drugs that treat inflammation through a variety of different mechanisms, it is still not feasible to successfully treat inflammatory disorders. Therefore, there is a need for developing new agents with action mechanisms different from the conventional anti-inflammatory drugs. Interestingly, prenylated flavonoids and its derivatives with anti-inflammatory activities have been reported continuously (Han´akova´et al., 2015).

A series of prenylated flavonoids and its derivatives ( 11 , 79 , 80 , 273–291 ) ( Figs. 3 and 9 ) were obtained and their anti-inflammatory activity was tested ( Table 5 ) (Han´akova´et al., 2017; Hoˇsek et al., 2011;
;
;
;
;
;
;
). The results showed that most of prenylated flavonoids possessed moderate anti-inflammatory activity in LPS-stimulated RAW 264.7 cells through down-regulated COX-2 induction at 10–25 μM. Particularly, cudraflavone B ( 282) is a prenylated flavonoid containing a cyclized prenyl group on the ring A, bearing an additional 2 ′ ,4 ′ -OH moiety on the ring B, which exhibited the most potent anti-inflammatory activity via inhibiting the activity of COX-2. This effect is comparable to that of the typical COX inhibitor indomethacin (COX-2, IC 50 = 2.5 μM for compound 282 and 1.9 μM for indomethacin), showing that compound 282 is a strong COX-2 inhibitor and has some potential as a new nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug lead. Based on these data, the SARs displayed the position of a cyclic prenyl side chain on the ring A and 2 ′ ,4 ′ -OH moiety on the ring B of prenylated flavonoid skeleton, which played an important role for anti-COX activity.

In 2011, Jeran et al. reported that 5,7,4 ′ -trihydroxy-6-geranylflavanone ( 292 ) ( Fig. 9 ), a prenylated flavonoid derivative isolated from the fruits of
Artocarpus commun
is ( Moraceae ), showed a great anti-inflammatory property in vitro (
). According to their study, low concentration of compound 292 (≤2.5 μM) showed a great inhibitory effect on gene expression of RAGE, and down-regulated both TNF-α and IL-1β secretion and gene expression in THP-1 cells. Podoverine B ( 293 ) ( Fig. 9 ), a prenylated flavanone-flavonol dimer isolated from plant callus culture, and exhibited potent anti-inflammatory activity through inhibition of macrophage chemiluminescence (IC 50 = 6.4 μM) (
). Additionally, the production of a typical pro-inflammatory cytokine TNF-α in LPS stimulated macrophages was used to determine the anti-inflammatory activity of prenylated flavonoids ( 33 , 283 , 294–319 ) ( Fig. 9 ) ( Table 5 ) (Han´akova´et al., 2015, 2017; Zelova´et al., 2014). The outcome exhibited that compounds 283 and 294–297 were most efficient in significantly inhibiting the secretion of TNF-α. More importantly, compound 296 (IC 50 < 10 μM) displayed the strongest inhibitory activity with an effect nearly twice that of the positive control prednisone.

Nitric oxide (NO) is a short-lived radical gas and cellular signaling molecule generated from 
L
-arginine catalyzed by nitric oxide synthase (NOS) (

). Inducible NOS will produce high levels of NO, which plays an important role in regulating immunomodulatory and inflammatory responses (

; 

). However, excessive production of NO can lead to inflammatory diseases in the immune system. Thus, inhibiting the production of NO can provide a new way to find the potential anti-inflammatory drugs.

