Alzheimer’ s disease (AD) is an age-related progressive neurodegenerative disease, characterized by progressive and irreversible cognitive deterioration, memory loss and behavioral disturbances (

). It is an alarming fact that three-quarters of the world’ s population older than 60 years of age are expected to suffer from AD by 2025 according to the World Health Organization (

). To date, no consensus has been reached on the cause of AD. However, with the increasing research on AD, several hypotheses have been proposed based upon the various pathophysiological factors observed, including amyloid beta (Aβ) peptide deposits, deficits of acetylcholine (ACh), tau protein aggregation, dyshomeostasis of biometals, and oxidative stress (

). Prenylated flavonoids, an important class of small molecule natural polyphenolic phytochemicals, have been reported to be effective in the treatment of AD.

The cholinesterases (ChEs) serve as the key enzymes which are highly implicated in the pathogenesis of AD, and the ChEs inhibitors might be more effective for the prevention and treatment of AD. During the study of screening for the anti-AD activity of the traditional medicine 

