The increasing development of bacterial resistance to antibiotics is a major difficulty to the successful treatment of infectious diseases caused by bacteria (

). Due to the characteristic of rapid spread, the bacteria can be easily and quickly carried from one continent to another, which poses huge threats to public health (

). There is an urgent need for developing novel antimicrobial agents without cross resistance to successful treatment of the disease 
caused by bacteria
. In 
this context, many researcher groups have concentrated their efforts on developing effective antimicrobial agents without cross resistance. Natural products have particularly been a rich source of anti-infective agents, so many semisynthetic or synthetic compounds with remarkable anti-infective activities have been designed and synthesized by lead optimization of natural scaffolds
(

). 
Prenylated
flavonoids have been reported for protective role against microbial invasion in the plants. Due to this protective role, this class of natural products is becoming the subject of anti-infective research.

Malaria is the major parasitic infection and remains one of the most prevalent and mortal diseases in the world, principally in Sub Saharan Africa (

). In view of resistance even to newly introduced drugs, continued efforts to develop new antimalarial drugs are needed (

). The prenylated flavonoid scaffold can be considered as a promising skeleton for further exploiting new effective anti-parasite drugs (

).

The high levels of free radicals in living systems are harmful to human health, which mainly caused cell death, tissue damage and various diseases such as neurological disease, inflammation, cancer, arteriosclerosis and cardiovascular disease through oxidizing the biomolecules (

). The antioxidants mainly act through scavenging radicals, mostly hydroxyl radicals, and thereby inhibiting the chain of oxidative events that leads to damage of proteins and lipid membranes. In addition, by inhibiting superoxide anion and reactive oxygen species (ROS) production, degrading hydrogen peroxide and chelating or reducing metal ions, the antioxidants play an essential role in the human health (

). Several methods have been frequently used to estimate antioxidant capacity in free radical biology such as 1,1-diphenyl-2-picrylhydrazyl (DPPH) radical assays, 2,2-azino-- bis-3-ethylbenzthiazoline-6-sulphonic acid (ABTS 
•+
) scavenging assays, and ferric reducing antioxidant power (FRAP) assays. It was reported that prenylated flavonoids have well known antioxidant activity via several pathways.

Xiuli Zhang and co-workers systematically evaluated the antioxidant activity of xanthohumol ( 431 ) ( Fig. 16 ), the major prenylated flavonoid in beer, using three systems including ABTS •+ , DPPH, and FRAP assays ( Table 9 ) (
). The result showed xanthohumol exhibited remarkable antioxidant activity in the ABTS •+ and FRAP assays with TEAC (Trolox as equivalent antioxidant capacity) values of 0.31 and 0.27 μM/L, respectively. From the study of Jan Hosek and co-workers, the natural prenylated flavonoids ( 82 , 287 , 432–433 ) ( Figs. 3 ,
9
, 16 ) were also screened for their scavenging activity against three reactive oxygen species (O 2 • , H 2 O 2 , and HClO) (
). Among these compounds, compound 287 contained two hydroxyl moieties at positions C-3 ′ and C-4 ′ on the B-ring, and exhibited the highest level of scavenging activity against superoxide radicals and hydrogen peroxide with IC 50 values of 41.2 ± 3.7 and 554.0 ± 45.8 μM, respectively. The outcome demonstrated that bearing the catechol moiety on the B-ring of prenylated flavonoids significantly improved the antioxidant activity.

Diabetes is a kind of metabolic disease affecting more and more people all over the world. Various enzymes like a-glucosidase, protein kinase C (PKC), PPAR-γ (peroxisome proliferator activated receptor-γ) are linked directly or indirectly with diabetes. The disease can be controlled by various anti-diabetic agents through various acting mechanisms, such as increase in insulin secretion from pancreatic β- cells (sulphonylureas), enhancement of insulin action (PPAR-γ agonists) and reduction of hepatic glucose production (α- glucosidase inhibitors) (

; 

; 

). Interestingly, prenylated flavonoids have been reported for the treatment of diabetes through inhibiting α- glucosidase or activating PPAR-γ.

Several prenylated flavonoids ( 445–451 ) ( Fig. 17 ) was isolated from the roots of
Dorstenia psilurus (Moraceae)
, and their α- glucosidase inhibitory activity was evaluated by using the slightly modified method of Matsu et al. ( Table 10 ) (
). Among them, compound 445 with three unmodified prenyl groups exhibited the best α- glucosidase inhibitory activity (IC 50 = 4.13 μM), while compound 450 , with only one prenyl group, showed the worst α- glucosidase inhibitory activity (IC 50 = 43.95 μM). It was observed that α- glucosidase inhibitory activity increased with the number of unmodified prenylated groups present, which suggested that the prenyl side chain could be important for α- glucosidase inhibitory activity. In addition, a series of prenylated flavonoids ( 370 , 452–465 ) ( Figs. 12 and 17 ) and other compounds were isolated from Herba Epimedii ( Berberidaceae ), subsequently, the PPAR-γ ligand binding activity of these isolates was evaluated by using a GAL-4-PPAR-γ chimera assay system (
). The result indicated that these prenylated flavonoids exhibited more potent activity than other isolates, which implied that prenyl units has been linked to an increased affinity to the PPAR-γ.

Estrogens have been shown to exert a variety of beneficial effects on the human health, such as providing protection against menopausal symptoms, osteoporosis, cardiovascular disease, and some potentially neurodegenerative diseases. Moreover, estrogens are also one of the most important risk factors for breast cancer (

). As estrogen-like compounds play a crucial role in preventing and treating estrogen-mediated diseases, searching for estrogen-like compounds with remarkable activities has been an attractive area for science community (

). Phytoestrogens are the non-steroidal plant-derived compounds that functionally mimic mammalian estrogens. Thus, they are also considered to play an important role in preventing menopausal symptoms, osteoporosis, cancer and heart disease (

).

Cardiovascular disease has gradually become the highest incidence and more people die from the disease than from any other cause in the world annually, according to the World Health Organization report. Existing researchers have found that one of the main causes for cardiovascular diseases is the involvement of vascular tissues through losing their capacity to relax. Therefore, in order to effectively treat cardiovascular disease, many research groups have paid much attention to the vascular studies (

; 

; 

).

Some prenylated flavonoids and their derivatives 472–494 ( Fig. 19 ) were designed and synthesized by the Yongzhou Hu and co-workers according to the predictive results of support vector machine (SVM) classification model, and their vasodilatory activity were evaluated against phenylephrine (PE)-induced contraction in rat thoracic aorta rings model (
,
). Among these compounds, compounds 483 , 485 and 493 exhibited potent vasorelaxant activity. Particularly, (±) leachianone G 483 which bearing 8-prenyl on the A ring and 2 ′ ,4’-(OH) 2 on the B ring exhibited the most potent vasorelaxant activity (EC 50 : 9.3 μM, Emax: 94.9%). SAR studies of prenylated flavonoids revealed that flavanones showed the most potent vasorelaxant activity, while flavones and chalcones exhibited medium activity. In addition, existence of prenyl group at A-ring and 2 ′ ,4’-(OH) 2 substitution at B-ring contributed to a better vasorelaxant activity.

Tyrosinase plays an essential role for melanin synthesis in mammals, and its overproduction will result in skin hyperpigmentations, such as melasma, chloasma and age spots (

). In addition, compared with normal cells, the expression level of tyrosinase in tumor cells was significantly up-regulated and its activity also increased (

; 

). Thus, tyrosinase inhibitors have attracted considerable attention from drug researchers. Interestingly, many reports have proved that prenylated flavonoids exhibited remarkable tyrosinase inhibitory activity through different mechanisms of action (

; 

; 

).

The tyrosinase inhibitory activity of nine prenylated flavonoids ( 12 , 33 , 77 , 495–499 ) ( Figs. 3 and 20 ) ( Table 12 ) was evaluated (
;
