The indoleamine 2,3-dioxygenase 1 (IDO1), a tryptophan catabolising enzyme, is known as a tumour cell survival factor that can cause immune escape in several types of cancer. Therefore, the development of IDO1 inhibitors has attracted more and more attention from researchers (
). Six prenylated flavonoids ( 531–536 ) ( Fig. 20 ) were obtained from
Sophora flavescens (Fabaceae)
and their IDO1 inhibitory activity was evaluated ( Table 12 ) (
). Among these compounds, 536 with two prenyl side chain at position C-6 and C-8 respectively, showed the strongest inhibitory effects with IC 50 values of 4.3 μM, and the subsequent molecular docking analysis also revealed that the prenyl residues of compound 536 had binding affinity to residues of IDO1. Thus, the prenyl side chain at the skeleton of prenylated flavonoids could be important for IDO1 inhibitory activity.

The phosphodiesterases (PDEs) mainly catalyze the hydrolysis of the cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP) and cyclic guanosine monophosphate (cGMP) (
). Given the critical roles of cAMP and cGMP in physiologic processes, PDEs has become an important drug target for treatment of various diseases such as congestive heart failure, pulmonary hypertension and schizophrenia (
). A series of prenylated flavonoids ( 33 , 537–550 ) ( Figs. 3 and 20 ) was isolated from the traditional Chinese medicine
Morus alba (Moraceae)
, and their inhibitory activity against phosphodiesterase-4 (PDE4) was evaluated ( Table 13 ) (
). The result indicated that most of these isolates showed remarkable inhibitory activity against PDE4 with IC 50 values ranging from 0.0054 to 0.40 μM, which was more potent than the positive control rolipram (IC 50 = 0.62 μM). Particularly, compound 537 exhibited the most potent inhibitory activity with IC 50 value of 0.0054 μM, and molecular dynamics simulations revealed that the prenyl moiety could be an important pharmacophore to improve the activity. Furthermore, in order to construct a small prenylated flavonoid library for the structure-activity relationship (SAR) study, compound 79 , the major component in the
Morus alba (Moraceae)
and obtained in large amount, served as the starting material to semi-synthesize its derivatives. A total of 13 derivatives ( 551–563 ) were synthesized through methylation, esterification, hydrogenation, silanization and oxidative cyclization ( Fig. 21 ) (
). Unfortunately, the result indicated that most derivatives were less active than the parent compound 79 ( Table 13 ). For PDE4, the key SARs which dramatically improved the activities could be summarized. (a) presence of prenyl moiety at C-3 and C-8 seems to be more contribute to the significant inhibitory activity (compounds 33 , 537–540 , 543 , 545 and 549 ); (b) formation of 2 H -pyran ring D between C-9 and 2 ′ -OH promotes the improvement of activity (compounds 537 and 538 vs 79 ).

Up to now, most of the prenylated flavonoids with one or two prenyl side-chain on the A ring can be synthesized by various synthetic schemes. Van-Son Nguyen and Kingsadingthongkham Vongdeth et al. published the classical synthesis of C-8-prenylated flavonoids using the 2,4,6-trihydroxyacetophenone as starting material ( Fig. 23 ) (Nguyen et al., 2015;
). The methoxymethyl (MOM) group was chosen to protect hydroxy group on the benzene ring, under a series of reactions including aldol condensation, cyclization, oxidation with dimethyldioxirane (DMDO) and selective 5-demethoxymethyl protection yielding 3,7,4 ′ -tri- O -(methoxymethoxyl) kaempferol ( i1 ). Subsequently, the intermediate i1 was treated with prenyl bromide and K 2 CO
3 in
acetone at reflux, yielding the prenyl ether ( i2 ), following the microwave-assisted Claisen rearrangement in N , N -diethylaniline to obtain the desired para-prenylated flavonoid with 82% yield, which is the key step in the whole synthesis process. Besides, from the study of Elisa Nuti et al., while 5- O -prenylflavonoid was treated with N , N -dimethylaniline at 200 ◦ C without microwave irradiation, only 42% of the para-rearranged product was obtained and the ortho-rearranged product was found to be the major product (
). It suggested that the microwave irradiation plays a crucial role in the regioselective synthesis C-prenylated flavonoid.

Furthermore, in order to address the poor selectivity of prenyl being rearrangement to flavonoids C-6 and C-8, Alberto Minassi et al. reported the method of straight synthesis of C-6 and C-8 prenylflavonoids via Wessely-Moser rearrangement (
;
;
). In spite of the fact that TBDMS group was more stable than other groups under the basic conditions [heating in toluene in the presence of Eu(fod) 3 ], thus, the TBDMS was chosen to protect the hydroxy group of 2,4,6-trihydroxyacetophenone ( Fig. 24 ). The intermediate i3 have been synthesized by Mitsunobu reaction, and it subsequently was treated with catalytic amounts of Eu(fod)
3 in
chloroform, Claisen-Cope product i4 was obtained in high yields through this method (
). The key C-prenyl intermediate i4 was next pivaloylated to i5 and then chemoselectively ortho-desily lated by mild acidolysis with TFA in THF/water, affording the key C-prenyl intermediate
i 6
in excellent yield. Finally, under Brønsted acid catalysis and Wessely-Moser rearrangement, the key C-prenyl intermediates i4 and i6 are regioselectively converted to C-6 prenyl and C-8 prenyl flavones, respectively.

Emerging evidence has shown that the position, number and length of prenyl group on the B-ring also have a marked influence on bioactivities of prenylated flavonoids, and methods for the synthesis prenyl side-chain on the B ring are being investigated by numerous researches (

; 

). Jinhui Yang and her research group have been working on synthesis of the prenylated flavonoids for many years. According to their study, the prenyl side-chain on the B ring can be synthesized by the delocalization of phenoxide anion within the aromatic ring and Claisen-Schmidt condensation (
Fig. 26
) (

, 

; 

). The key step was the introduction of the prenyl group to hydroxybenzaldehyde, which proceeded into an unsatisfactory yield. But many medicinal chemists have tried other methods for the prenylation on the phenyl group without much success (

).

To the best of our knowledge, the majority of natural prenylated flavonoids are C-prenylated derivatives. Under the catalyzed action of regiospecific prenyltransferases, C-prenylation was generated frequently at position 6/8 on ring A or at position 3’/5 ′ on ring B, which are usually ortho to a phenolic hydroxyl group with rich electrons, and generated occasionally at C-3 on ring C, which is also more or less electron rich due to the conjugation (
). Xu et al. reported a convenient route to direct synthesis of C-3 prenylated flavonoids. Alkylation of the key intermediate i16 with 3-methylbut-2-enyl bromide was carried out using LDA as the bases ( Fig. 27 ). Subsequent aldol condensations of i17 with various benzaldehydes were therefore carried out using NaHMDS in THF, and the chalcones i18 was synthesized. Finally, C-3 prenylated flavonoids were obtained by the cyclization with simultaneous deprotection under refluxing intermediate
i 18
in acid (
;
;
).
